ired specifically for the DVLA’s forms etc.</p><p>5) Note that DVSA did not come into existence until 2014/15 with the merger of the DSA and VOSA – the figure shown for spend on tablets and ipads relates to DSA only.</p>","South Holland and The Deepings","Mr John Hayes",,"2017-03-08T17:52:47.813Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/706268/answer","Biography information for Sir John Hayes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/706268/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/706268/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-02-28","Department for Transport: ICT","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, how much his Department spent on (a) iPads and tablets and (b) paper in each of the last five years for which figures are available.","false","Biography information for Justin Madders","Ellesmere Port and Neston","Justin Madders","65992"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/706269","Department for Transport","false","2017-03-08","<p>I refer the hon. Member to my answer on 28 February 2017, to Question UIN 64552.</p><p> </p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2017-03-08T12:03:26.657Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/706269/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/706269/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/706269/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-02-28","Department for Transport: Brexit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, pursuant to the Answer of 28 February 2017 to Question 64552, what discussions his Department had with the Department for Exiting the European Union on the drafting of the White Paper entitled The United Kingdom's exit from and new partnership with the European Union, Cm 9417, published in February 2017.","false","Biography information for Paul Blomfield","Sheffield Central","Paul Blomfield","66006"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/706270","Department for Transport","false","2017-03-06","<p>The Secretary of State has an approval role under the Ticketing and Settlement Agreement for changes to the National Rail Conditions of Travel.</p><p> </p><p>The Rail Delivery Group is responsible for the management of the National Rail Conditions of Travel and it is for them to propose changes to the Secretary of State for approval.</p><p> </p>","Blackpool North and Cleveleys","Paul Maynard",,"2017-03-06T15:46:58.88Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/706270/answer","Biography information for Paul Maynard","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/706270/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/706270/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-02-28","Railways: Compensation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, whether his Department plans to review the National Rail Conditions of Travel to ensure compliance with consumer protection laws.","true","Biography information for Andy McDonald","Middlesbrough","Andy McDonald","65975"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/706271","Department for Transport","false","2017-03-06","<p>The Government is not required to collect information on compensation paid by train operators to their customers under the Consumer Rights Act 2015, which came into force for all transport providers on 1 October 2016, and does not hold this information.</p><p> </p><p>It is the responsibility of train operators to ensure that their customers are made aware of their rights to compensation or other redress in cases of service failure or disruption. Train operators’ existing compensation schemes provide the main means of redress for passengers.</p>","Blackpool North and Cleveleys","Paul Maynard",,"2017-03-06T15:43:55.427Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/706271/answer","Biography information for Paul Maynard","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/706271/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/706271/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-02-28","ScotRail: Compensation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, if the Government will provide a breakdown of compensation paid to passengers under the Consumer Rights Act 2015 by ScotRail.","false","Biography information for Andy McDonald","Middlesbrough","Andy McDonald","65972"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/706272","Department for Transport","false","2017-03-08","<p>The Government expects highway authorities to work towards high-quality, attractive and inclusive streets that work for people of all abilities.</p><p> </p><p>The Department’s Local Transport Note 2/08 is a guidance document for local authorities and already encourages local authority designers to keep in mind the needs of disabled persons. The provisions of The Public Service Equality Duty are binding on those bodies in the public sector who provide any service. For that reason local authorities must be able to show that they have complied with this Duty in providing infrastructure for cyclists and our revised LTN will provide appropriate guidance for local authorities.</p><p> </p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2017-03-08T13:40:20.93Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/706272/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/706272/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/706272/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-02-28","Cycling","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, pursuant to the Answers of 16 January and 9 February 2017 to Questions 58966 and 63857, if he will take steps to ensure that the planned revision of his Department's Local Transport Note LTN 2/08, Cycle Infrastructure Design, complies with the Public Sector Equality Duty by setting out design standards which progressively enable anyone to take up cycling as a safe, convenient and normal means of travel, regardless of age, gender and ability.","false","Biography information for Ruth Cadbury","Brentford and Isleworth","Ruth Cadbury","65946"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/706273","Department for Transport","false","2017-03-06","<p>(a) In the current December 2016 timetable, which applies between11 December 2016 and 20 May 2017, CrossCountry operate the following number of services between Birmingham and Bristol which call at Gloucester:</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p><strong>Day</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Southbound</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Northbound</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Monday to Friday</p></td><td><p>2</p></td><td><p>1</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Saturday</p></td><td><p>1</p></td><td><p>1</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Sunday</p></td><td><p>1</p></td><td><p>1</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p>(b) CrossCountry have operated the current franchise since 2007. In 2001 when the franchise was operated by Virgin Trains, the following services were provided between Birmingham and Bristol which call at Gloucester:</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p><strong>Day</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Southbound</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Northbound</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Monday to Friday</p></td><td><p>8</p></td><td><p>6</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Saturday</p></td><td><p>8</p></td><td><p>7</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Sunday</p></td><td><p>6</p></td><td><p>7</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p>The information for 2001 in table (b) is based on the September 2000 timetable compiled by Railtrack (now Network Rail), which applied between 24 September and19 May 2001 and constitutes the only information available to the Department for Transport. Numbers of services on Saturdays and Sundays were subject to minor fluctuation, dependent on when engineering works were scheduled during the September 2000 to May 2001 timetable.</p>","Blackpool North and Cleveleys","Paul Maynard",,"2017-03-06T15:35:10.107Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/706273/answer","Biography information for Paul Maynard","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/706273/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/706273/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-02-28","Cross country railway line: Gloucester","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, how many trains per day there were travelling between Birmingham and Bristol that stopped at Gloucester in (a) the last year and (b) 2001.","false","Biography information for Richard Graham","Gloucester","Richard Graham","65924"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/706274","Department for Transport","false","2017-03-08","<p>Where noise from the construction of HS2 is likely to impact a person’s home by exceeding the relevant limits, the Government will offer to install noise insulation in the property, or pay for the costs of installing noise insulation. Noise insulation will also be offered to eligible properties that experience noise impacts above the relevant limits from the operation of HS2 services.</p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2017-03-08T12:00:25.36Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/706274/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/706274/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/706274/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-02-28","High Speed 2 Railway Line","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, if he will provide financial support for the soundproofing of properties affected by noise from the High Speed 2 line.","false","Biography information for Hilary Benn","Leeds Central","Hilary Benn","66014"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/706275","Wales Office","false","2017-03-08","<p>The UK Government is working constructively with local partners and the Welsh Government towards a city deal for the Swansea Bay City Region. I am determined that we work together to achieve a great deal for the region, which we will announce as soon as we are able. Given the advanced stage of the negotiations on a deal it would not be appropriate for me to release the contents of correspondence with strategic partners.</p><p> </p>","Vale of Glamorgan","Alun Cairns","65903 ; 65938","2017-03-08T16:19:21.05Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/706275/answer","Biography information for Alun Cairns","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/706275/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/706275/answer",,,,,"28","Wales","Wales","2017-02-28","Swansea Bay City Region: Correspondence","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Wales, what written correspondence he has had with the Swansea City Region Board in the last 12 months; and if he will place copies of any such correspondence in the Library.","false","Biography information for Jonathan Edwards","Carmarthen East and Dinefwr","Jonathan Edwards","65936"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/706276","Wales Office","false","2017-03-08","<p>The UK Government is working constructively with local partners and the Welsh Government towards a city deal for the Swansea Bay City Region. I am determined that we work together to achieve a great deal for the region, which we will announce as soon as we are able. Given the advanced stage of the negotiations on a deal it would not be appropriate for me to release the contents of correspondence with strategic partners.</p><p> </p>","Vale of Glamorgan","Alun Cairns","65903 ; 65936","2017-03-08T16:19:21.113Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/706276/answer","Biography information for Alun Cairns","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/706276/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/706276/answer",,,,,"28","Wales","Wales","2017-02-28","City Region Deals: Swansea Bay","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Wales, whether he has informed HM Treasury of his decision on the proposed Swansea Bay City Region deal.","false","Biography information for Jonathan Edwards","Carmarthen East and Dinefwr","Jonathan Edwards","65938"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/706277","Wales Office","false","2017-03-07","<p>My Department continues to have regular discussions with the Department for Exiting the European Union to ensure our exit from the EU is a success. We are committed to working closely with the devolved administrations and stakeholders across the United Kingdom to build a stronger, fairer more global Britain.</p><p> </p>","Vale of Glamorgan","Alun Cairns",,"2017-03-07T11:46:31.46Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/706277/answer","Biography information for Alun Cairns","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/706277/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/706277/answer",,,,,"28","Wales","Wales","2017-02-28","Wales Office: Brexit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Wales, pursuant to the Answer of 27 February 2017 to Question 64554, what discussions his Department had with the Department for Exiting the European Union on the drafting of the White Paper entitled The United Kingdom's exit from and new partnership with the European Union, Cm 9417, published in February 2017.","false","Biography information for Paul Blomfield","Sheffield Central","Paul Blomfield","66004"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/706278","Wales Office","false","2017-03-07","<p>The Wales Office purchased an iPad in May 2012 at a cost of £434 but has purchased no other iPads or tablets in the last five years.</p><p> </p><p>We do not hold information on how much the Department has spent on paper.</p><p> </p>","Aberconwy","Guto Bebb",,"2017-03-07T11:47:52.62Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/706278/answer","Biography information for Guto Bebb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/706278/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/706278/answer",,,,,"28","Wales","Wales","2017-02-28","Wales Office: Public Expenditure","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Wales, how much his Department spent on (a) iPads and tablets and (b) paper in each of the last five years for which figures are available.","false","Biography information for Justin Madders","Ellesmere Port and Neston","Justin Madders","65994"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/706279","Women and Equalities","false","2017-03-04","<p>The Equality and Human Rights Commission is an independent body and makes its own decisions about handling discrimination and equal pay claims. I have therefore asked the Chief Executive of the Commission to write to the honourable member with the information requested. I will place a copy of the letter in the libraries of both Houses.</p>","Gosport","Caroline Dinenage",,"2017-03-04T09:50:16.81Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/706279/answer","Biography information for Caroline Dinenage","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/706279/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/706279/answer",,,,,"31","Women and Equalities","Women and Equalities","2017-02-28","Equality and Human Rights Commission: Expenditure","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for Women and Equalities, how much the Equality and Human Rights Commission has spent settling discrimination and equal pay claims (a) internally, (b) before an employment tribunal determination and (c) after an employment tribunal determination in the last 10 years.","false","Biography information for Philip Davies","Shipley","Philip Davies","65952"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/706280","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-03-08","<p>The Government and its agencies have brought a renewed focus to the health and safety system by working to: maintain the gains made in safety at work, while giving health the same priority; keep people in work through good health and safety management; and help people return to work through the right support and advice. This approach looks to build on the considerable strengths of the health and safety system whilst addressing its continuing challenges: the ever-changing nature of work and the needs of an increasingly ageing population.</p><p> </p><p>The approach is under pinned by three key strategies: the Government’s Green Paper, <em>Work, Health and Disability: Improving Lives</em>, which sets out the Government’s proposals for improving work and health outcomes for people with long-term health conditions; HSE’s <em>Health and Work Strategy</em>, which addresses the occupational health problems which most commonly afflict the working population; and the strategy for Great Britain’s wider occupational health and safety system, <em>Helping Great Britain work well</em>.</p><p><strong> </strong></p><p>This combined approach seeks active participation of business and the wider community in delivering lasting health and safety benefits as these issues cannot be addressed by the Government, and its agencies, acting in isolation.</p>","Portsmouth North","Penny Mordaunt",,"2017-03-08T13:32:11.153Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/706280/answer","Biography information for Penny Mordaunt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/706280/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/706280/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-02-28","Industrial Health and Safety","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what steps the Government and Government agencies are taking to work together to reduce work-related illness and deaths.","false","Biography information for Stephen Pound","Ealing North","Stephen Pound","65959"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/706281","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-03-08","<p><strong> </strong></p><p>(a) The amount spent on iPads and tablets in each of the last 5 years is as follows:</p><table><tbody><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p><strong>12/13</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>13/14</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>14/15</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>15/16</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>16/17</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Total</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>iPads</p></td><td><p>£ -</p></td><td><p>£ -</p></td><td><p>£ 3,169</p></td><td><p>£ 2,876</p></td><td><p>£ 2,759</p></td><td><p><strong> £ 8,803 </strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Tablets</p></td><td><p>£ -</p></td><td><p>£ -</p></td><td><p>£ 3,638</p></td><td><p>£ 3,661,288</p></td><td><p>£ 15,367</p></td><td><p><strong> £ 3,680,293 </strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>Total</strong></p></td><td><p><strong> £ - </strong></p></td><td><p><strong> £ - </strong></p></td><td><p><strong> £ 6,806 </strong></p></td><td><p><strong> £ 3,744,163 </strong></p></td><td><p><strong> £ 18,127 </strong></p></td><td><p><strong> £ 3,769,096 </strong></p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p>All figures are inclusive of VAT and relate to the cost of the device only.</p><p> </p><p>Purchases of tablets relate to the deployment of tablets to replace laptops for certain categories of end user.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p>(b) We have the following spend data for Office copier paper:</p><table><tbody><tr><td><p><strong>2012/13</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2013/14</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2014/15 </strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2015/16</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2016/17 (YTD 01/17) </strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>£2,543,643</p></td><td><p>£2,173,328</p></td><td><p>£1,670,000</p></td><td><p>£1,400,000</p></td><td><p>£1,011,000</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes",,"2017-03-08T17:25:05.217Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/706281/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/706281/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/706281/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-02-28","Department for Work and Pensions: ICT","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how much his Department spent on (a) iPads and tablets and (b) paper in each of the last five years for which figures are available.","false","Biography information for Justin Madders","Ellesmere Port and Neston","Justin Madders","65995"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/706282","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-03-06","<p>This information is not available.</p><p> </p><p>Information on Jobseeker’s Allowance and Employment and Support Allowance sanction decisions, by referral reason and geography, is available here: <a href="https://stat-xplore.dwp.gov.uk/" target="_blank">https://stat-xplore.dwp.gov.uk</a></p><p> </p><p>Guidance for users is available at: <a href="https://sw.stat-xplore.dwp.gov.uk/webapi/online-help/Getting-Started.html" target="_blank">https://sw.stat-xplore.dwp.gov.uk/webapi/online-help/Getting-Started.html</a></p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds",,"2017-03-06T14:52:36.21Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/706282/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/706282/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/706282/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-02-28","Social Security Benefits: Yorkshire and the Humber","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how many benefit claimants have been sanctioned for being late by jobcentres in Yorkshire and the Humber since 2015.","false","Biography information for Louise Haigh","Sheffield, Heeley","Louise Haigh","65999"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/706283","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-03-06","<p>The information requested is not available. However, such information that is available is in the tables and provides the number of (a) Jobseeker’s Allowance and Universal Credit (required to seek work) claimants; plus the number of new claims to (b) Employment and Support Allowance and Income Support from people who are required to attend Whitley Bay Jobcentre.</p><p> </p><p>Table (a) The number of Jobseeker’s Allowance and Universal Credit (required to seek work) claimants required to attend Whitley Bay Jobcentre</p><p><strong> </strong></p><table><tbody><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p>The number of Jobseeker’s Allowance and Universal Credit claimants required to attend Whitley Bay Jobcentre</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Position at January 2017</p></td><td><p>400</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p><strong> </strong></p><p>Table (b) The number of new claims to Employment and Support Allowance and Income Support from people required to attend Whitley Bay Jobcentre</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>Position For 12 Month Period <strong> </strong></p></td><td><p>The number of people making a new claim to Employment and Support Allowance required to attend Whitley Bay Jobcentre</p></td><td><p>The number of people making a new claim to Income Support required to attend Whitley Bay Jobcentre</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>January 2016 to December 2016</p></td><td><p>554</p></td><td><p>47</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p><strong> </strong></p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds",,"2017-03-06T12:01:44.497Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/706283/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/706283/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/706283/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-02-28","Jobcentres: Whitley Bay","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how many people are registered at Whitley Bay Jobcentre.","false","Biography information for Sir Alan Campbell","Tynemouth","Mr Alan Campbell","66035"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/706284","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-03-06","<p>Throughout the development of these proposals, the Department has been mindful of its duties under section 149 of the Equality Act 2010. Consideration of the potential impact on staff and customers has been informed by statistical analysis of population data, local knowledge and consultation.</p><p> </p><p>As we obtain further local, site-specific information for all sites, including those in the Liverpool Wavertree constituency, we will ensure any issues identified are also taken fully into consideration when the final decisions are made. We intend to complete this work within the next 12 weeks; equality analysis is not generally published separately but it will be used to inform final decisions.</p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds",,"2017-03-06T11:41:03.16Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/706284/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/706284/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/706284/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-02-28","Jobcentres: Liverpool","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, if he will publish the equality impact assessment reports his Department has undertaken on jobcentre closures in Liverpool, Wavertree constituency.","false","Biography information for Luciana Berger","Liverpool, Wavertree","Luciana Berger","66025"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/706285","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-03-06","<p>The information requested is not available. However, such information that is available is (a) the number of Lone Parents claiming Income Support within Liverpool Wavertree Parliamentary Constituency; plus in the table (b) the number of new claims by Lone Parents to Income Support who are registered at Wavertree and Edge Hill Jobcentres.</p><p> </p><p>(a) The number of Lone Parents claiming Income Support within Liverpool Wavertree Constituency at August 2016 is 770.</p><p> </p><p>(b) The number of new claims by Lone Parents to Income Support who are registered at Wavertree and Edge Hill Jobcentres.</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>Period</p></td><td><p>The number of new claims by Lone Parents to Income Support who are registered at Wavertree Jobcentre</p></td><td><p>The number of new claims by Lone Parents to Income Support who are registered at Edge Hill Jobcentre</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>January 2016 to December 2016</p></td><td><p>60</p></td><td><p>103</p></td></tr></tbody></table>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds",,"2017-03-06T11:48:51.1Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/706285/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/706285/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/706285/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-02-28","Jobcentres: Liverpool","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how many lone parents are registered at the jobcentre in (a) Wavertree and (b) Edge Hill.","false","Biography information for Luciana Berger","Liverpool, Wavertree","Luciana Berger","66026"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/706286","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-03-06","<p>The Department has used information from local transport provider websites, such as Traveline, that provide services in Liverpool to calculate travel costs.</p><p> </p><p>Distances and journey times have been calculated using variety of methods to improve accuracy, including Google Maps which has been cross verified using the AA route mapping tool and information collected about local public transport routes with input from local DWP colleagues.</p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds",,"2017-03-06T12:06:47.323Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/706286/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/706286/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/706286/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-02-28","Jobcentres: Liverpool","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, pursuant to the Answer of 17 February 2017 to Question 64229, on jobcentres in Liverpool, which local public transport route planner applications his Department used in those calculations.","false","Biography information for Luciana Berger","Liverpool, Wavertree","Luciana Berger","66027"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/706287","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-03-06","<p>There are no daily work clubs at Wavertree Jobcentre or Edge Hill Jobcentre.</p><p> </p><p>Jobcentre Plus does not contract for the delivery of Work Clubs and we are not responsible for the delivery. Work Clubs can be set up or supported by any suitable group including voluntary sector organisations, local authorities, community groups, and both local employers, and national employers through their local outlets. The role of Jobcentre Plus is to signpost claimants to local Work Clubs where they exist and where advisers believe the support offered will help the claimant find work. There is no requirement for follow up on the number of claimants who subsequently attend.</p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds",,"2017-03-06T12:12:30.087Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/706287/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/706287/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/706287/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-02-28","Jobcentres: Liverpool","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what assessment his Department has made of the number of people who use (a) Wavertree and (b) Edge Hill jobcentres to attend daily work clubs.","false","Biography information for Luciana Berger","Liverpool, Wavertree","Luciana Berger","66028"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/706288","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-03-06","<p>The Department announced its proposals for Whitley Bay Jobcentre on 26 January 2017. The full list of sites we have announced has been published and is available from the Gov.uk website at this address: <a href="http://qna.files.parliament.uk/ws-attachments/678953/original/DWP%20Estates%20Proposals.pdf" target="_blank">http://qna.files.parliament.uk/ws-attachments/678953/original/DWP%20Estates%20Proposals.pdf</a>.</p><p> </p><p>Since 1998 the Department occupies the majority of its accommodation under a Private Finance Initiative (PFI) known as the PRIME contract. Under the terms of this 20-year PFI, the Department contracts to occupy fully serviced accommodation from its private sector partner, Telereal Trillium.</p><p> </p><p>The lease for the building in question is included within the provisions of this PFI arrangement and is therefore not held directly by DWP. Telereal Trillium was informed of the proposals to close Whitley Bay Jobcentre on 26 January 2017.</p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds",,"2017-03-06T14:47:26.927Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/706288/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/706288/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/706288/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-02-28","Jobcentres: Whitley Bay","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, on what date his Department (a) announced proposals to close Whitley Bay Jobcentre Plus and (b) informed the current landlords of that property of that decision.","false","Biography information for Sir Alan Campbell","Tynemouth","Mr Alan Campbell","66038"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/706289","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-03-08","<p>The Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy was created by merging the Department for Energy and Climate Change (DECC) with parts of the Department for Business, Innovation and Skills (BIS). The amounts spent by BIS and DECC was as follows:</p><p>BIS</p><table><tbody><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p>FY 11-12</p></td><td><p>FY 12-13</p></td><td><p>FY 13-14</p></td><td><p>FY 14-15</p></td><td><p>FY 15-16</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Paper</p></td><td><p>*</p></td><td><p>*</p></td><td><p>*</p></td><td><p>£14,115</p></td><td><p>£3,088</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>iPads</p></td><td><p>*</p></td><td><p>*</p></td><td><p>*</p></td><td><p>£5,510</p></td><td><p>£0</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p>*Figures for the 11/12, 12/13 and 13/14 financial years cannot be provided without incurring disproportionate cost</p><p>DECC</p><table><tbody><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p>FY 11-12</p></td><td><p>FY 12-13</p></td><td><p>FY 13-14</p></td><td><p>FY 14-15</p></td><td><p>FY 15-16</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Paper</p></td><td><p>**</p></td><td><p>**</p></td><td><p>**</p></td><td><p>**</p></td><td><p>£13,643.64</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>iPads</p></td><td><p>**</p></td><td><p>**</p></td><td><p>**</p></td><td><p>£900</p></td><td><p>£22,494</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p>**Figures for the 11/12, 12/13, 13/14 and 14/14 (paper only) financial years cannot be provided without incurring disproportionate cost</p>","Stourbridge","Margot James",,"2017-03-08T16:45:37.11Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/706289/answer","Biography information for Margot James","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/706289/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/706289/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-02-28","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy: ICT","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, how much his Department spent on (a) iPads and tablets and (b) paper in each of the last five years for which figures are available.","false","Biography information for Justin Madders","Ellesmere Port and Neston","Justin Madders","65976"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/706290","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-03-08","<p>Companies House is not required to identify limited partnerships in such a way as to ascertain whether they are qualifying partnerships under The Companies and Partnerships (Accounts and Audit) Regulations 2013. Consequently, it does not capture this information in any direct way and could only obtain it at disproportionate cost.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","Stourbridge","Margot James","65997 ; 65998","2017-03-08T17:20:10.28Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/706290/answer","Biography information for Margot James","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/706290/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/706290/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-02-28","Companies: Scotland","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, how many Scottish limited partnerships are qualifying partnerships under the terms of The Companies and Partnerships (Accounts and Audit) Regulations 2013.","false","Biography information for Roger Mullin","Kirkcaldy and Cowdenbeath","Roger Mullin","65996"
