"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/705579","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2017-03-06","<p>The UK is a signatory to the Memorandum of Understanding (MoU) on the Conservation and Management of Marine Turtles and their Habitats of the Indian Ocean and South-East Asia and discusses implementation of the MoU with other signatory states at its triennial meetings. At the last meeting in September 2014, which the UK attended, signatory states discussed a number of turtle enforcement issues.</p><p> </p>","Suffolk Coastal","Dr Thérèse Coffey",,"2017-03-06T15:10:37Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/705579/answer","Biography information for Dr Thérèse  Coffey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/705579/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/705579/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2017-02-27","Turtles: Conservation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what representations she has made to her international counterparts on ensuring that legislation introduced to protect turtles and their habitat is being enforced.","false","Biography information for Helen Goodman","Bishop Auckland","Helen Goodman","65710"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/705580","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2017-03-06","<p>The UK Government has provided funding of around £550,000 to protect turtles.</p><p> </p><p>The Darwin Initiative has funded projects seeking to protect turtles in developing countries and in the UK Overseas Territories. A current Darwin project is promoting the conservation and sustainable use of marine turtles in Southwest Madagascar. Another, led by the University of Exeter, is working in Peru to find a solution to the thousands of endangered turtles who die as a result of gillnet fisheries around the world by employing the use of light emitting diodes (LEDs).</p><p> </p><p>Through the Overseas Territories Environment and Climate fund, also known as Darwin Plus, Defra has funded a project in the Cayman Islands assessing how best to reduce threats to wild marine turtles.</p><p> </p><p>The Flagship Species Fund, a partnership between Defra and Fauna and Flora International (FFI), has supported all six of the world’s hard-shelled marine turtle species and most recently funded a project supporting sea turtle conservation through applied research in Anguilla.</p>","Suffolk Coastal","Dr Thérèse Coffey","65712","2017-03-06T15:30:00.037Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/705580/answer","Biography information for Dr Thérèse  Coffey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/705580/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/705580/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2017-02-27","Turtles: Conservation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what funding the Government has provided to projects seeking to protect turtles.","false","Biography information for Helen Goodman","Bishop Auckland","Helen Goodman","65711"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/705581","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2017-03-06","<p>The UK Government has provided funding of around £550,000 to protect turtles.</p><p> </p><p>The Darwin Initiative has funded projects seeking to protect turtles in developing countries and in the UK Overseas Territories. A current Darwin project is promoting the conservation and sustainable use of marine turtles in Southwest Madagascar. Another, led by the University of Exeter, is working in Peru to find a solution to the thousands of endangered turtles who die as a result of gillnet fisheries around the world by employing the use of light emitting diodes (LEDs).</p><p> </p><p>Through the Overseas Territories Environment and Climate fund, also known as Darwin Plus, Defra has funded a project in the Cayman Islands assessing how best to reduce threats to wild marine turtles.</p><p> </p><p>The Flagship Species Fund, a partnership between Defra and Fauna and Flora International (FFI), has supported all six of the world’s hard-shelled marine turtle species and most recently funded a project supporting sea turtle conservation through applied research in Anguilla.</p>","Suffolk Coastal","Dr Thérèse Coffey","65711","2017-03-06T15:30:00.11Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/705581/answer","Biography information for Dr Thérèse  Coffey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/705581/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/705581/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2017-02-27","Turtles: Conservation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what funding and other support the Government provides for research into the conservation of turtles.","false","Biography information for Helen Goodman","Bishop Auckland","Helen Goodman","65712"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/705582","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2017-03-08","<p>We, and other Departments, are working closely with the Department for Exiting the European Union on all aspects of exiting the European Union.</p><p> </p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice",,"2017-03-08T11:57:30.61Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/705582/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/705582/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/705582/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2017-02-27","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs: Brexit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what (a) EU agencies and other organisations within her Department's remit the Government plans to withdraw from when the UK leaves the EU, (b) staff time was spent on engagement with those bodies and (c) financial resources were spent on engagement with those bodies in 2015-16.","false","Biography information for Maria Eagle","Garston and Halewood","Maria Eagle","65640"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/705583","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2017-03-02","<p>To assess how the country can be better protected from future flooding and extreme weather events the Government established the National Flood Resilience Review (NFRR). It identified a number of actions to strengthen our resilience. Good progress is being made on the implementation of these recommendations. All infrastructure companies have completed initial assessments of their vulnerable sites for suitability for temporary flood defences. As a result companies have invested heavily in resilience measures to prepare for this winter.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The Government is working with utility companies to improve permanent defences in the longer term. This is being overseen by an inter-Ministerial group which has been established to oversee flooding policy, including the implementation of the NFRR recommendations.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","Suffolk Coastal","Dr Thérèse Coffey",,"2017-03-02T14:42:21.087Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/705583/answer","Biography information for Dr Thérèse  Coffey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/705583/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/705583/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2017-02-27","Flood Control","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what recent assessment she has made of the effectiveness of long-term flood resilience strategies.","false","Biography information for Mr Jim Cunningham","Coventry South","Mr Jim Cunningham","65667"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/705584","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-03-02","<p>We have received a number of questions from MPs, MSPs, AMs, customers and other representatives as well as from public consultations for sites that are outside of the criteria we have set. We are conducting public consultation on all proposals to close or move a Jobcentre outside of these criteria to help determine any impacts that additional travel will have on claimants.</p><p> </p><p>Throughout the development of our proposals, the Department has been mindful of its duties under section 149 of the Equality Act 2010. Our continued focus on equality analysis will be important in helping to assess the needs of disabled people. Full equality analysis covering all sites where changes are proposed, will be carried out in due course to inform the final decision making process. This assessment will take into account feedback we have received for sites where we have undertaken public consultation and help establish the need for any alternative provision, such as outreach services.</p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds",,"2017-03-02T12:46:16.09Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/705584/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/705584/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/705584/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-02-27","Jobcentres: Closures","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what representations he has received on the effect of the proposed closure of Jobcentre Plus offices on disabled people.","false","Biography information for Mr Jim Cunningham","Coventry South","Mr Jim Cunningham","65668"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/705585","Department of Health","false","2017-03-07","<p>The Government is convinced that increasing folic acid intake of women who are either planning to get pregnant or are pregnant is the right course for the health and development of the unborn baby. It has therefore looked carefully at the evidence for mandatory fortification of flour. On balance, the Government decided that this is not the right way forward and therefore has no plans to introduce it for England. The Government recommends that, whatever their age, women who are either planning to get pregnant, or who are pregnant, should take a 400 microgram folic acid supplement before and during the early days of pregnancy.</p>","Oxford West and Abingdon","Nicola Blackwood",,"2017-03-07T10:50:58.143Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/705585/answer","Biography information for Baroness Blackwood of North Oxford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/705585/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/705585/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-02-27","Flour: Folic Acid","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what his Department's policy is on mandatory fortification of flour with folic acid.","false","Biography information for Baroness Ritchie of Downpatrick","South Down","Ms Margaret Ritchie","65707"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/705586","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2017-03-06","<p>Defra does not hold information on local authority payments to the Driver and Vehicle Licensing Agency (DVLA) for air quality improvement purposes.</p><p> </p>","Suffolk Coastal","Dr Thérèse Coffey",,"2017-03-06T14:41:18.507Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/705586/answer","Biography information for Dr Thérèse  Coffey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/705586/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/705586/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2017-02-27","Air Pollution","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what information her Department holds on local authority payments to the DVLA for air quality improvement purposes.","false","Biography information for Charlotte Leslie","Bristol North West","Charlotte Leslie","65582"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/705587","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2017-03-06","<p>The Government will bring forward legislation in the next session that, when enacted, will repeal the European Communities Act 1972 and ensure a functioning statute book on the day we leave the EU. This ‘Great Repeal Bill’ will end the authority of EU law and return power to the UK.</p><p> </p><p>All Government departments are currently reviewing the issues and opportunities arising from exit, including any requirements for legislation in addition to the Great Repeal Bill.</p><p> </p><p>The Government will bring forward a White Paper on the Great Repeal Bill in due course that provides more detail about our approach. We will ensure it is published in time to allow Parliament sufficient time to digest its contents in advance of introduction of the Great Repeal Bill in the next session.</p><p> </p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice",,"2017-03-06T14:49:28.337Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/705587/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/705587/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/705587/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2017-02-27","Common Agricultural Policy and Common Fisheries Policy","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what assessment she has made of the need for new legislation resulting from replacement of the Common Agricultural Policy and Common Fisheries Policy after the UK leaves the EU.","false","Biography information for Caroline Lucas","Brighton, Pavilion","Caroline Lucas","65633"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/705588","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2017-03-02","<p>We have yet to decide whether to formally participate in this campaign. Our proposals, however, to ban the use of microbeads in cosmetics and personal care products as well as our wider approach to addressing marine litter are consistent with the aims of the campaign.</p><p> </p>","Suffolk Coastal","Dr Thérèse Coffey",,"2017-03-02T14:32:22.427Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/705588/answer","Biography information for Dr Thérèse  Coffey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/705588/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/705588/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2017-02-27","Marine Environment: Litter","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, if the Government will participate in the UN Clean Seas global campaign on marine litter.","false","Biography information for Kerry McCarthy","Bristol East","Kerry McCarthy","65619"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/705589","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2017-03-06","<p>The Common Agricultural Policy’s Greening requirements, which include the crop diversification rule, were implemented in 2015.</p><p> </p><p>As we prepare to leave the EU, we are looking at removing the rules that are unnecessarily burdensome, focusing instead on what works best for the UK. We want to free our farmers to grow more, sell more and export more British food, whilst upholding our high standards for the environment and animal health and welfare.</p><p> </p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice","65795","2017-03-06T15:34:20.9Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/705589/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/705589/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/705589/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2017-02-27","Crops: EU Action","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, if she will seek to delay the EU's proposed three-crop diversification scheme's implementation.","false","Biography information for Grant Shapps","Welwyn Hatfield","Grant Shapps","65794"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/705590","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2017-03-06","<p>The Common Agricultural Policy’s Greening requirements, which include the crop diversification rule, were implemented in 2015.</p><p> </p><p>As we prepare to leave the EU, we are looking at removing the rules that are unnecessarily burdensome, focusing instead on what works best for the UK. We want to free our farmers to grow more, sell more and export more British food, whilst upholding our high standards for the environment and animal health and welfare.</p><p> </p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice","65794","2017-03-06T15:34:20.96Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/705590/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/705590/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/705590/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2017-02-27","Crops: EU Action","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, if she will make an assessment of the effect that the EU's proposed three-crop diversification scheme will have on the UK's farming economy.","false","Biography information for Grant Shapps","Welwyn Hatfield","Grant Shapps","65795"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/705591","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2017-03-02","<p>Highly Pathogenic Avian Influenza (of strain H5N8) has been circulating in Europe since the autumn of 2016. There have been 10 confirmed cases in poultry in the UK and several findings in wild birds.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>As part of our Department’s continued measures to control and eradicate H5N8, a new Avian Influenza Prevention Zone was put in place on 28 February. This zone continues to require that all keepers of poultry and captive birds observe heightened biosecurity requirements regardless of their location. Subject to these measures being put in place, the majority of keepers will no longer be required to house their birds.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>Within England, there are some areas that are at a higher risk of H5N8 due to their proximity to substantial inland or coastal bodies of water where wild waterfowl collect. The identification of these areas was based on expert advice in regards to the latest veterinary and ornithological data and has been reviewed by leading experts. In these Higher Risk Areas, which will cover around 25 per cent of poultry premises, mandatory housing or the full range netting of outside areas will be required. This may temporarily result in the loss of Free Range status for keepers in these areas unless they apply netting of range, rather than housing.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>During this unprecedented period of high risk, the Secretary of State has taken a decision which is based on the best scientific and veterinary advice in order to control disease and protect our poultry industry. Effective disease control will always be Defra’s priority: disease outbreaks cause birds to suffer, damage businesses and cost the UK taxpayer millions. No significant disruption to the supply of Free Range eggs after 28 February is anticipated.</p><p> </p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice",,"2017-03-02T16:39:09.933Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/705591/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/705591/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/705591/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2017-02-27","Avian Influenza: Disease Control","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what assessment she has made of the effect on free-range producers of the definition of new avian flu higher risk areas; and if she will make a  statement.","false","Biography information for Anne-Marie Trevelyan","Berwick-upon-Tweed","Mrs Anne-Marie Trevelyan","65760"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/705592","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-03-07","<p>We continue to advocate the importance of a peaceful and fair electoral process in Cambodia. It is in the interests of long-term stability in the country for there to be free and fair elections that command the confidence of the voters. In support of this the EU, with UK support, has provided financial and technical assistance to the National Electoral Commission in the preparation of a new voter registry in advance of the upcoming Commune and General elections. We look to the authorities to ensure an environment in which opposition parties and civil society can function freely.</p>","Reading West","Alok Sharma",,"2017-03-07T15:07:08.187Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/705592/answer","Biography information for Alok Sharma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/705592/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/705592/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-02-27","Cambodia: Politics and Government","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what steps the Government is taking to promote democracy and free and fair elections in Cambodia.","false","Biography information for Daniel Kawczynski","Shrewsbury and Atcham","Daniel Kawczynski","65731"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/705593","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-03-07","<p>The Government is gravely concerned about demolition of Palestinian property by the Israeli authorities, including plans to demolish the Bedouin village of Khan al Ahmar. I raised this issue with the Israeli Ambassador to London on 1 March. Officials from our Embassy in Tel Aviv last raised our concerns with the Israeli authorities on 28 February.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood",,"2017-03-07T16:16:25.717Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/705593/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/705593/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/705593/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-02-27","West Bank: Demolition","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, if he will make urgent representations to the Israeli Government to consider reversing the recent demolition orders served to the village of Khan al- Ahmar in the occupied West Bank.","false","Biography information for Julie Elliott","Sunderland Central","Julie Elliott","65732"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/705594","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-03-07","<p>The Moldovan Government has stated on a number of occasions that it is committed to the recovery of assets lost as a result of the 2014 bank fraud. Ongoing investigations are a matter for the relevant Moldovan authorities.</p>","Uxbridge and South Ruislip","Boris Johnson",,"2017-03-07T14:12:47.653Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/705594/answer","Biography information for Boris Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/705594/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/705594/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-02-27","Moldova: Fraud","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what recent assessment he has made of the progress of efforts by the Government of Moldova to recover assets lost as a result of bank fraud.","false","Biography information for Emily Thornberry","Islington South and Finsbury","Emily Thornberry","65775"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/705595","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-03-07","<p>We have made clear to the Government of the Republic of Moldova that we expect it to deliver on its reform commitments as a matter of urgency. The Moldovan Government has made a moderately promising start with legislative reforms to the justice sector, and the strengthening of the banking system following the 2014 bank fraud, but these initial steps need to be underpinned by full implementation and concrete results and Moldova still has a long way to go on judicial and economic reform and fighting corruption.</p><p>The UK is providing support to judicial and economic reform and fighting corruption, including through the Good Governance Fund (GGF). Through the GGF we plan to fund up to £4.3 million worth of projects and programmes in Financial Year 16/17, including projects which focus on these areas specifically. We plan a similar allocation in Financial Year 17/18. GGF support has already helped improve the resilience of the banking and financial sectors through supervisory and regulatory reform and contributed to improving sentencing procedures for corruption crimes, by developing sentencing guidelines as well as recommendations for their application.</p>","Uxbridge and South Ruislip","Boris Johnson",,"2017-03-07T14:44:04.997Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/705595/answer","Biography information for Boris Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/705595/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/705595/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-02-27","Moldova: Corruption","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what steps he is taking to support efforts by the Government of Moldova to (a) investigate and (b) prosecute allegations of official corruption in that country.","false","Biography information for Emily Thornberry","Islington South and Finsbury","Emily Thornberry","65776"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/705596","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-03-07","<p>We share the assessment of the Organization for Security and Co-operation in Europe/Office for Democratic Institutions and Human Rights Election Observation Mission which covered the first and second rounds of the Presidential elections in Moldova on 30 October and 13 November 2016. The OSCE/ODIHR concluded that both rounds were competitive with respect for fundamental freedoms. They also noted, however, that the electoral process was marred by widespread abuse of administrative resources, lack of campaign finance transparency and unbalanced media coverage with politically affiliated broadcasters portraying some candidates in an increasingly negative tone, especially in the run-up to the second round. We urge the Moldovan authorities to consider measures to deal with these priorities for the future.</p>","Uxbridge and South Ruislip","Boris Johnson","65781","2017-03-07T14:48:37.81Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/705596/answer","Biography information for Boris Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/705596/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/705596/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-02-27","Moldova: Elections","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what assessment he has made of the fairness of the media coverage in Moldova of the Presidential elections held in that country in October and November 2016.","false","Biography information for Emily Thornberry","Islington South and Finsbury","Emily Thornberry","65777"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/705597","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-03-07","<p>While we have not discussed US settlements policy with the Israeli authorities, we welcome President Trump's interest in working for a peace deal that meets the requirements of both parties. The UK's view remains that the two-state solution is the best option to achieve that. We continue to believe settlements are one of a number of significant barriers to achieving a two-state solution and regularly raise our concerns about settlement activity with the Israeli authorities.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood",,"2017-03-07T16:11:21.153Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/705597/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/705597/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/705597/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-02-27","Israeli Settlements","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what discussions he has had with his counterparts in the Israeli Government on US policy on the construction of settlements in the Palestinian territories since the US President's meeting with the Israeli Prime Minister on 15 February 2017.","false","Biography information for Judith Cummins","Bradford South","Judith Cummins","65727"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/705598","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-03-07","<p>The UK fully supports the work of the EU Border Assistance Mission to Moldova and Ukraine (EUBAM) and the active role it is playing in supporting both Moldova and Ukraine in border management. No recent UK assessments have been made of the security of the border between the Transnistria region of Moldova and Ukraine. Part of the state border between the Republic of Moldova and Ukraine is under the control of the <em>de facto </em>Transnistrian authorities and the <em>de jure </em>Moldovan authorities are unable to exercise any effective control on the side of the state border outside their effective control.</p>","Uxbridge and South Ruislip","Boris Johnson",,"2017-03-07T14:45:18.483Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/705598/answer","Biography information for Boris Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/705598/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/705598/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-02-27","Trans-Dniestr: Ukraine","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what recent assessment he has made of the security of the border between the Transnistria region of Moldova and Ukraine.","false","Biography information for Emily Thornberry","Islington South and Finsbury","Emily Thornberry","65778"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/705599","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-03-07","<p>I have not discussed this matter with either the Government of India or Pakistan. The longstanding position of the United Kingdom is that it is for India and Pakistan to find a lasting resolution to the situation in Kashmir, taking into account the wishes of the Kashmiri people. It is not for the United Kingdom to prescribe a solution or to act as a mediator. We encourage both sides to maintain positive dialogue, but the pace and scope of this is for them to determine.</p>","Reading West","Alok Sharma",,"2017-03-07T15:06:13.633Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/705599/answer","Biography information for Alok Sharma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/705599/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/705599/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-02-27","Kashmir","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what discussions he has had on the matter of self-determination for Azad Kashmir with his counterparts in the Government of (a) India and (b) Pakistan.","false","Biography information for Judith Cummins","Bradford South","Judith Cummins","65728"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/705600","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-03-07","<p>The Russian military presence in the Transnistria region of Moldova is made up of two components. The first is the Russian contingent to the Tripartite Peace Keeping force established under the 1992 Cease Fire Agreement between the Republic of Moldova and the Russian Federation. The number of Russian military personnel currently serving as part of the Tripartite Peace Keeping force is estimated at around 420 soldiers.</p><p>The second component of Russian military personnel in the Transnistria region of Moldova is the 8th Operational Group of Russian Forces (OGRF) Brigade. These forces do not have host nation (Moldovan) consent. The number of Russian military personnel currently serving in the 8th OGRF Brigade is estimated at around 1500 soldiers.</p><p>Continuing to station the 8th OGRF Brigade in the Transnistria region without the consent of the Republic of Moldova places the Russian Federation in breach of commitments it entered into at the 1999 Organization for Security and Co-operation in Europe Istanbul Summit. We fully support calls for the Russian Federation to remove from the territory of the Republic of Moldova those elements of its armed forces and munitions which do not have host nation consent.</p>","Uxbridge and South Ruislip","Boris Johnson",,"2017-03-07T14:46:57.313Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/705600/answer","Biography information for Boris Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/705600/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/705600/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-02-27","Trans-Dniestr: Russia","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what recent estimate he has made of the number of Russian military personnel in the Transnistria region of Moldova.","false","Biography information for Emily Thornberry","Islington South and Finsbury","Emily Thornberry","65779"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/705601","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-03-07","<p>The agreed themes of the UK-United Arab Emirates (UAE) Year of Culture season are Next Generation, Community and Inclusion.</p><p>Through the Inclusion and Community themes, the British Council aims to make the UK-UAE Year of Culture programme accessible to all sectors of society, including those with special needs, the elderly and disabled.</p><p>The Next Generation theme focuses on capacity building for the UAE youth to enable them to participate fully in society.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood",,"2017-03-07T16:14:06.137Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/705601/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/705601/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/705601/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-02-27","United Arab Emirates: Human Rights","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, how the issue of respect for human rights is reflected in the programme for the UK-UAE Year of Culture.","false","Biography information for Tom Brake","Carshalton and Wallington","Tom Brake","65729"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/705602","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-03-07","<p>The establishment of a NATO liaison office in Chisinau was requested by the Moldovan Government. The Parliament of the Republic of Moldova has ratified the exchange of letters necessary for the office to proceed and the Government understands the office is likely to open in June 2017. NATO is committed to supporting Moldova's reform efforts and both NATO and the UK share the objective of wishing to see a secure and stable Moldova. The Republic of Moldova is, however, a constitutionally neutral country that does not aspire to NATO membership, something which both the UK and NATO acknowledge and respect.The British Ambassador to Moldova met the Head of the NATO Office (designate) in Chisinau on 3 March.</p>","Uxbridge and South Ruislip","Boris Johnson",,"2017-03-07T16:03:42.113Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/705602/answer","Biography information for Boris Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/705602/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/705602/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-02-27","Moldova: NATO","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what discussions he has had with his Moldovan counterpart on the planned opening of a permanent NATO liaison office in Chisinau.","false","Biography information for Emily Thornberry","Islington South and Finsbury","Emily Thornberry","65780"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/705603","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-03-07","<p>We share the assessment of the Organization for Security and Co-operation in Europe/Office for Democratic Institutions and Human Rights Election Observation Mission which covered the first and second rounds of the Presidential elections in Moldova on 30 October and 13 November 2016. The OSCE/ODIHR concluded that both rounds were competitive with respect for fundamental freedoms. They also noted, however, that the electoral process was marred by widespread abuse of administrative resources, lack of campaign finance transparency and unbalanced media coverage with politically affiliated broadcasters portraying some candidates in an increasingly negative tone, especially in the run-up to the second round. We urge the Moldovan authorities to consider measures to deal with these priorities for the future.</p>","Uxbridge and South Ruislip","Boris Johnson","65777","2017-03-07T14:48:37.857Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/705603/answer","Biography information for Boris Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/705603/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/705603/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-02-27","Moldova: Elections","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what assessment he has made of the fairness of the conduct of Presidential elections in Moldova held in October and November 2016.","false","Biography information for Emily Thornberry","Islington South and Finsbury","Emily Thornberry","65781"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/705604","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-03-07","<p>The last formal round of 5+2 talks on the Transnistria unresolved conflict took place on 2-3 June 2016 in Berlin under the German Chairmanship of the Organization for Security and Co-operation in Europe (OSCE). The 5+2 consists of the OSCE as the Chair, Moldova and Transnistria as the parties to the conflict, the Russian Federation and Ukraine as the mediators, and the EU and United States as observers. The UK is not party to the 5+2 process and consequently not represented at meetings of the 5+2, although we follow the process closely.</p><p>The UK welcomed the resumption of formal 5+2 talks last year and encouraged the sides to remain committed to the process, to engage constructively, and to deliver on the commitment made in Berlin to engage in dialogue via Working Groups on key issues including telecommunications, legal authentication of university diplomas and ecology.</p><p>Austria assumed the Chairmanship of the OSCE in January 2017. There is as yet no date set for the next formal round of 5+2 talks.</p><p>The UK remains committed to supporting a comprehensive, peaceful settlement of the Transnistria unresolved conflict based on the sovereignty and territorial integrity of the Republic of Moldova with a special status for the Transnistria region.</p>","Uxbridge and South Ruislip","Boris Johnson","65804","2017-03-07T15:02:36.92Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/705604/answer","Biography information for Boris Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/705604/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/705604/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-02-27","Trans-Dniestr","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, who represented the Government at the most recent round of 5+2 talks on the status of the Transnistria region of Moldova; and what assessment the Government has made of the outcome of those talks.","false","Biography information for Emily Thornberry","Islington South and Finsbury","Emily Thornberry","65805"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/705605","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-03-07","<p>The Republic of Moldova is not a Candidate Country. The UK remains committed to supporting reform, embedding stability and addressing shared challenges such as security and migration in the Eastern Neighbourhood. We fully support the Association Agreement (AA) which aims to deepen political and economic relations between Moldova and the EU.</p>","Uxbridge and South Ruislip","Boris Johnson",,"2017-03-07T14:53:33.52Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/705605/answer","Biography information for Boris Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/705605/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/705605/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-02-27","Moldova: EU Enlargement","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what recent assessment he has made of the prospects for future Moldovan membership of the EU; and what the Government's policy is on potential Moldovan membership of the EU.","false","Biography information for Emily Thornberry","Islington South and Finsbury","Emily Thornberry","65802"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/705606","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-03-07","<p>Moldova has made a promising start on implementation of the ambitious political, governance and economic reforms agreed under the EU-Moldova Association Agreement, which was provisionally applied from September 2014 and entered into force on 1 July 2016 following ratification by all EU Member States. The Association Agreement which, includes the introduction of a Deep and Comprehensive Free Trade Area, supports Moldova's economic growth by providing both EU market access and an impetus for modernising reforms. The key sectors where reforms are needed include the rule of law and judicial sector reform, a reformed public sector administration, and financial and banking sector reform.</p><p>The British Government monitors progress closely and encourages and supports the Moldovan Government to maintain momentum across the board, and in particular on judicial reform and in tackling corruption where more work is needed by Moldova to further embed democratic institutions. The UK's Good Governance Fund (GGF) is funding a project to provide easy access to the general public, media and the business sector on the implementation of the Deep and Comprehensive Free Trade Area with the aim of stimulating corresponding trade opportunities.</p>","Uxbridge and South Ruislip","Boris Johnson",,"2017-03-07T14:59:09.3Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/705606/answer","Biography information for Boris Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/705606/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/705606/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-02-27","Moldova: EU External Relations","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what assessment he has made of the progress made in implementing the Association Agreement between the EU and Moldova.","false","Biography information for Emily Thornberry","Islington South and Finsbury","Emily Thornberry","65803"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/705607","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-03-07","<p>The last formal round of 5+2 talks on the Transnistria unresolved conflict took place on 2-3 June 2016 in Berlin under the German Chairmanship of the Organization for Security and Co-operation in Europe (OSCE). The 5+2 consists of the OSCE as the Chair, Moldova and Transnistria as the parties to the conflict, the Russian Federation and Ukraine as the mediators, and the EU and United States as observers. The UK is not party to the 5+2 process and consequently not represented at meetings of the 5+2, although we follow the process closely.</p><p>The UK welcomed the resumption of formal 5+2 talks last year and encouraged the sides to remain committed to the process, to engage constructively, and to deliver on the commitment made in Berlin to engage in dialogue via Working Groups on key issues including telecommunications, legal authentication of university diplomas and ecology.</p><p>Austria assumed the Chairmanship of the OSCE in January 2017. There is as yet no date set for the next formal round of 5+2 talks.</p><p>The UK remains committed to supporting a comprehensive, peaceful settlement of the Transnistria unresolved conflict based on the sovereignty and territorial integrity of the Republic of Moldova with a special status for the Transnistria region.</p>","Uxbridge and South Ruislip","Boris Johnson","65805","2017-03-07T15:02:36.747Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/705607/answer","Biography information for Boris Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/705607/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/705607/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-02-27","Trans-Dniestr","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, when he expects the next round of 5+2 talks on the status of the Transnistria region of Moldova to be held; and what the Government's priorities will be for those discussions.","false","Biography information for Emily Thornberry","Islington South and Finsbury","Emily Thornberry","65804"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/705608","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-03-07","<p>The UK is deeply concerned for the welfare of the Rohingya community in Burma. When meeting with members of the Bangladesh government during my visit to Dhaka from 2 to 4 March, I welcomed the humanitarian assistance provided by Bangladesh to the Rohingya people and discussed how the UK and Bangladesh can work together to encourage a durable solution in Burma. I also received a briefing on the situation with the Rohingya refuges from UN agencies working on the ground in the Cox's Bazar area.</p><p>The Minister of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, my noble Friend, the Rt Hon. the Baroness Anelay of St Johns discussed the issue of Rohingya refugees when she met with the Bangladesh High Commissioner in February. I also raised the matter with the Bangladesh High Commissioner in November.</p>","Reading West","Alok Sharma",,"2017-03-07T15:08:35.237Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/705608/answer","Biography information for Alok Sharma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/705608/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/705608/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-02-27","Bangladesh: Refugees","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what representations his Department has made to authorities in Bangladesh on the relocation of Rohingya refugees to the Cox's Bazar area.","false","Biography information for Mrs Anne Main","St Albans","Mrs Anne Main","65844"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/705609","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-03-07","<p>Following my response of 24 February, the Foreign Secretary raised human rights concerns with Egypt's President Sisi during his visit to Cairo on 25 February, emphasising the importance of a free and open society. The Foreign Secretary also met human rights defenders and civil society activists to gain a better understanding of the human rights situation in Egypt and hear their concerns.</p><p>We will continue to monitor the situation closely and urge the Egyptian Government to implement the human rights provisions contained in the constitution.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood",,"2017-03-07T16:05:49.257Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/705609/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/705609/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/705609/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-02-27","Egypt: Human Rights","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what representations he has made to the Government of Egypt on alleged human rights abuses in that country.","false","Biography information for Dr Paul Monaghan","Caithness, Sutherland and Easter Ross","Dr Paul Monaghan","65631"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/705610","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-03-07","<p>​I refer the hon. Member to the answer I gave on 24 February 2017 (PQ 63917).</p>","Reading West","Alok Sharma",,"2017-03-07T15:09:22.407Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/705610/answer","Biography information for Alok Sharma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/705610/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/705610/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-02-27","China: Human Rights","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what representations he has made to his Chinese counterpart on the treatment of human rights activists in that country.","false","Biography information for Dr Paul Monaghan","Caithness, Sutherland and Easter Ross","Dr Paul Monaghan","65632"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/705611","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-03-07","<p>The Government takes its arms export licensing responsibilities very seriously and operates one of the most robust arms export control regimes in the world. All export licence applications are assessed on a case-by-case basis against the Consolidated EU and National Arms Export Licensing Criteria, taking account of all relevant factors at the time of the application.</p><p>The conflict is making the delivery of commercial and humanitarian supplies into Yemen, and their onward distribution, extremely difficult. We continue to urge all parties to the conflict to take all reasonable steps to allow the delivery and distribution of aid, and to facilitate rapid and safe humanitarian access. We also call upon all sides to do everything possible to prevent civilian casualties and damage to civilian infrastructure.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood",,"2017-03-07T16:00:21.897Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/705611/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/705611/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/705611/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-02-27","Yemen: Military Intervention","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what assessment he has made of the potential effect of the Government's arms export policy to Saudi Arabia on the humanitarian situation in Yemen.","false","Biography information for Martyn Day","Linlithgow and East Falkirk","Martyn Day","65575"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/705612","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-03-07","<p>The Government recognises the importance of free movement of journalists to cover issues of global importance. This must be balanced against security and safety considerations. The Government currently advises against all travel to Yemen.</p><p>I last spoke to the Yemeni Foreign Minister Mikhlafi on 23 February. We discussed the importance of making progress towards a political settlement, including protecting human rights.</p><p> </p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood",,"2017-03-07T16:02:56.813Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/705612/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/705612/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/705612/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-02-27","Yemen: Press Freedom","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what recent discussions he has had with his Yemeni counterpart on the free entry and movement of journalists in that country.","false","Biography information for Alison Thewliss","Glasgow Central","Alison Thewliss","65579"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/705613","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-03-07","<p>​As set out in the recent White Paper (&quot;The United Kingdom’s exit from and new partnership with the European Union&quot;), the Government will discuss with the EU and Member States our future status and arrangements with regard to EU agencies. It would not be appropriate to prejudge the outcome of the negotiations.</p>","Rutland and Melton","Sir Alan Duncan",,"2017-03-07T15:40:34.437Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/705613/answer","Biography information for Sir Alan Duncan","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/705613/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/705613/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-02-27","Foreign and Commonwealth Office: Brexit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what (a) EU agencies and other organisations within his Department's remit the Government plans to withdraw from when the UK leaves the EU, (b) staff time was spent on engagement with those bodies and (c) financial resources were spent on engagement with those bodies in 2015-16.","false","Biography information for Maria Eagle","Garston and Halewood","Maria Eagle","65641"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/705614","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2017-03-06","<p>Defra contributes £3.3 million on an annual basis to the operation of the United Nations Environment Programme (UNEP). Defra also pays mandatory subscriptions to a range of UN conventions that the UK is signed up to relating to specific environmental issues that UNEP oversees including climate change, biological diversity and ecosystem management, international wildlife trade, organic pollutants, chemicals and waste.</p>","Suffolk Coastal","Dr Thérèse Coffey",,"2017-03-06T14:53:58.98Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/705614/answer","Biography information for Dr Thérèse  Coffey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/705614/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/705614/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2017-02-27","UN Environment Programme","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, whether the UK contributes financially to the United Nations Environment Programme.","false","Biography information for Helen Goodman","Bishop Auckland","Helen Goodman","65709"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/705615","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-03-07","<p>Spending for the department for financial years 2010-11 to 2015-16 can be found in the Foreign and Commonwealth Office annual report and accounts on the the <a href="http://www.gov.uk/" target="_blank">Gov.uk</a> website using the following weblink: <a href="http://www.gov.uk/government/publications" target="_blank">www.gov.uk/government/publications</a>.</p>","Rutland and Melton","Sir Alan Duncan",,"2017-03-07T15:33:15.877Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/705615/answer","Biography information for Sir Alan Duncan","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/705615/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/705615/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-02-27","Foreign and Commonwealth Office: Procurement","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what the procurement spend of his Department was in each year since 2010.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","65685"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/705616","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-03-07","<p>Following a peak in attacks last year, the British High Commissioner to Malawi raised the UK's concern about the rise in attacks against people with albinism with Malawi's Foreign Affairs Minister.</p><p>The President of Malawi has taken a strong public stance. The Police have made over 80 arrests and trials are underway, with harsher sentences now in place for those convicted. In May 2016, the President appointed a national technical committee to oversee the implementation of a National Response Plan to address the threat to people with albinism, but resourcing remains a challenge.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood",,"2017-03-07T17:28:24.257Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/705616/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/705616/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/705616/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-02-27","Malawi: Albinism","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what recent representations he has made to the Government of Malawi on the rise of albinism-related crimes in that country.","false","Biography information for Patrick Grady","Glasgow North","Patrick Grady","65714"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/705617","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-03-07","<p>The UN report a total of 115 attacks, including 20 murders, against people with albinism in Malawi since 2014. Attacks increased significantly in 2014/15, following a clampdown in neighbouring Tanzania. The trend has been decreasing, but we remain concerned about ongoing attacks.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood",,"2017-03-07T17:31:21.037Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/705617/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/705617/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/705617/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-02-27","Malawi: Albinism","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what assessment he has made of trends in the level of albinism-related crimes in Malawi.","false","Biography information for Patrick Grady","Glasgow North","Patrick Grady","65715"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/705618","Department of Health","false","2017-03-07","<p>Department of Health cash based procurement spend in each financial year 2010-11 to 2015-16 is reported in the following table:</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>Financial year</p></td><td><p>£ million</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2010-11</p></td><td><p>£391.2</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2011-12</p></td><td><p>£559.8</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2012-13</p></td><td><p>£601.6</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2013-14</p></td><td><p>£404.1</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2014-15</p></td><td><p>£403.1</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2015-16</p></td><td><p>£520.4</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p><strong> </strong></p><p>Department of Health spend is reported in line with the Crown Commercial Service category spend classification for the procurement of all goods and services.</p>","Warrington South","David Mowat",,"2017-03-07T14:58:03.607Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/705618/answer","Biography information for David Mowat","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/705618/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/705618/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-02-27","Department of Health: Procurement","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what the procurement spend of his Department was in each year since 2010.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","65687"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/705619","Department of Health","false","2017-03-07","<p>The Government is committed to implementing the Prime Minister’s Challenge on Dementia 2020, published in 2015.</p><p>We are giving local authorities access to an extra £3.5 billion for adult social care by 2020.</p><p>In the Local Government Finance Settlement, we brought forward access to £900 million of additional funding for social care over the next two years through the Social Care Precept and Adult Social Care Support Grant.</p><p>Taken together with the funding announced in Spending Review 2015, these changes mean that local government will have access to the funding it needs to increase social care spending every year in this Parliament.</p>","Warrington South","David Mowat",,"2017-03-07T10:35:24.03Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/705619/answer","Biography information for David Mowat","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/705619/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/705619/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-02-27","Dementia","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what steps his Department is taking to ensure that there is adequate funding for social care for people with dementia.","false","Biography information for Julie Elliott","Sunderland Central","Julie Elliott","65705"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/705620","Department of Health","false","2017-03-07","<p>This information is not held centrally.</p>","Warrington South","David Mowat",,"2017-03-07T10:34:09.293Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/705620/answer","Biography information for David Mowat","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/705620/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/705620/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-02-27","Dementia","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what estimate he has made of the number of hospital beds occupied by people with dementia in each of the last 12 months.","false","Biography information for Julie Elliott","Sunderland Central","Julie Elliott","65706"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/705621","Department of Health","false","2017-03-02","<p>In order for NHS England to formally consider a new or revised service specification, a number of associated reports and processes need to be completed. The Complex Gynaecological Services Clinical Reference Group (CRG) did start the process of developing a new service specification for ovarian cancer, however, this did not progress through the process. This was due to technical difficulties encountered during the Impact Assessment stage and included issues in identifying activity and the associated financial impact.</p><p> </p><p>In the subsequent period, CRGs have been restructured and the responsibility for this clinical area now resides with the Specialised Cancer Surgery CRG, within the National Cancer Programme of Care. In addition, NHS England has also published a revised process for service specification development (titled: ‘Methods’), which can be found at:</p><p><a href="https://www.england.nhs.uk/commissioning/spec-services/key-docs/" target="_blank">https://www.england.nhs.uk/commissioning/spec-services/key-docs/</a></p><p> </p><p>The Methods sets out the process for completing service specification work and, in accordance with this process, the Specialised Cancer Surgery CRG has been asked to consider progressing this work. The CRG Chair is due to discuss the matter with a representative of the Gynaecology CRG later this week and, following this, it is expected that the first step of the process will be completed by the middle of March 2017.</p>","Warrington South","David Mowat",,"2017-03-02T11:10:35.533Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/705621/answer","Biography information for David Mowat","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/705621/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/705621/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-02-27","Ovarian Cancer","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, when NHS England plans to publish its service specification on ovarian cancer.","false","Biography information for Mr Peter Bone","Wellingborough","Mr Peter Bone","65673"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/705622","Department of Health","false","2017-03-02","<p>The Department’s Policy Research Unit on Cancer Awareness Screening and Early Diagnosis has undertaken a qualitative research study in which members of the public were given access to available leaflets on ovarian cancer awareness and then participated in six focus groups and interviews on their acceptability and how they would be received and understood if included within the all clear screening results letter from the breast or cervical screening programme. This study is now complete and is being prepared for peer-reviewed publication. A further qualitative research study with professionals will commence when approval is received from the Health Research Authority.</p><p> </p><p>A second project is a synthesis of published incidence, mortality, stage distribution and stage-specific survival rates for ovarian cancer by age. The aim of this project is to identify which age group would be most likely to benefit from such an intervention, in terms of risk of ovarian cancer and room for improvement in stage at diagnosis. This project is also complete and is being prepared for peer-reviewed publication.</p>","Warrington South","David Mowat","65672","2017-03-02T11:12:41.327Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/705622/answer","Biography information for David Mowat","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/705622/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/705622/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-02-27","Ovarian Cancer: Screening","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what the results were of focus groups set up to establish how women respond to information on (a) screening results for and (b) other aspects of ovarian cancer.","false","Biography information for Mr Peter Bone","Wellingborough","Mr Peter Bone","65674"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/705623","Department of Health","false","2017-03-02","<p>The Department’s Policy Research Unit on Cancer Awareness Screening and Early Diagnosis has undertaken a qualitative research study in which members of the public were given access to available leaflets on ovarian cancer awareness and then participated in six focus groups and interviews on their acceptability and how they would be received and understood if included within the all clear screening results letter from the breast or cervical screening programme. This study is now complete and is being prepared for peer-reviewed publication. A further qualitative research study with professionals will commence when approval is received from the Health Research Authority.</p><p> </p><p>A second project is a synthesis of published incidence, mortality, stage distribution and stage-specific survival rates for ovarian cancer by age. The aim of this project is to identify which age group would be most likely to benefit from such an intervention, in terms of risk of ovarian cancer and room for improvement in stage at diagnosis. This project is also complete and is being prepared for peer-reviewed publication.</p>","Warrington South","David Mowat","65674","2017-03-02T11:12:41.267Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/705623/answer","Biography information for David Mowat","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/705623/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/705623/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-02-27","Ovarian Cancer: Screening","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what progress has been made on the inclusion of information on ovarian cancer in letters to patients containing the results of recent cervical and breast screening.","false","Biography information for Mr Peter Bone","Wellingborough","Mr Peter Bone","65672"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/705624","Department of Health","false","2017-03-02","<p>£30 million is being invested each year this Parliament to improve children and young people’s services for eating disorders. This new funding will be used to improve community based eating disorder services so patients are helped earlier and fewer need in-patient care.</p><p> </p><p>NHS England will set a new access standard, to be achieved by 2020, that 95% of patients to be treated within four weeks of their first contact with a designated healthcare professional. For urgent cases, the standard will be one week. The first data demonstrating performance against this standard will be published in May 2017.</p>","Oxford West and Abingdon","Nicola Blackwood",,"2017-03-02T10:39:00.153Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/705624/answer","Biography information for Baroness Blackwood of North Oxford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/705624/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/705624/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-02-27","Eating Disorders","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what recent assessment he has made of the adequacy of treatment provision for people diagnosed with eating disorders.","false","Biography information for Mr Jim Cunningham","Coventry South","Mr Jim Cunningham","65669"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/705625","Department of Health","false","2017-03-07","<p>73 clinical commissioning groups (CCGs) applied for Wave 2 funding under the diabetes prevention programme. Their bids were made as part of collaborative arrangements involving several CCGs, and not all CCGs will implement the programme at the same pace.</p><p>The estimated total cost of implementing the diabetes prevention programme to date, covering the wave 1 areas, is £12 million. Actual payments are dependent on the performance of providers. The details of these contracts are shown in the attached table. Contracts for Wave 2 are due to be approved and awarded in March 2017.</p><p>The attached table shows the lead CCGs that have applied for diabetes transformation funding for any of the following interventions (this does not include details of all CCGs that are involved with bids, as in some cases many CCGs collaborated to deliver a project):</p><p>- improving uptake of structured education for people with diabetes;</p><p>- improving the achievement of the treatment targets recommended by the National Institute for Health and Care Excellence;</p><p>- new or expanded multi-disciplinary footcare teams; and</p><p>- new or expanded diabetes inpatient specialist nursing services.</p>","Oxford West and Abingdon","Nicola Blackwood","65591 ; 65592","2017-03-07T17:15:39.89Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/705625/answer","Biography information for Baroness Blackwood of North Oxford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/705625/answer","PQ65590 attached table 1.xlsx ; PQ65590 attached table 2.xlsx","PQ65590 attached table 1.xlsx ; PQ65590 attached table 2.xlsx","PQ65590 attached table 1 ; PQ65590 attached table 2","PQ65590 attached table 1 ; PQ65590 attached table 2","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/705625/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-02-27","Diabetes","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, how many clinical commissioning groups have applied for Wave 2 funding under the Diabetes Prevention Programme.","false","Biography information for Keith Vaz","Leicester East","Keith Vaz","65590"
