"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/705693","Ministry of Justice","false","2017-03-06","<p>The number of registered appeals awaiting a hearing as at 30 September 2016 in the Immigration and Asylum Chamber were as follows:</p><p>(a) First-tier - 58,357</p><p>(b) Upper Tribunal – 1,401</p><p> </p><p>These figures are the most recent available official statistics. This information is covered by the Code of Practice.</p>","North East Hertfordshire","Sir Oliver Heald",,"2017-03-06T12:20:41.193Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/705693/answer","Biography information for Sir Oliver Heald","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/705693/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/705693/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2017-02-27","Immigration: Appeals","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what number of cases awaited a hearing at the immigration (a) First-tier and (b) Upper Tribunal at 1 February 2017.","false","Biography information for Keith Vaz","Leicester East","Keith Vaz","65584"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/705694","Ministry of Justice","false","2017-03-07","<p>Information on the Ministry of Justice procurement spend is set out in our annual report for each year. These reports can be found at:</p><p> </p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications</a></p>","Bracknell","Dr Phillip Lee",,"2017-03-07T17:12:34.493Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/705694/answer","Biography information for Dr Phillip Lee","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/705694/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/705694/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2017-02-27","Ministry of Justice: Procurement","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what the procurement spend of her Department was in each year since 2010.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","65691"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/705695","Ministry of Justice","false","2017-03-06","<p>As set out in the recent White Paper (The United Kingdom’s exit from and new partnership with the European Union), the Government will discuss with the EU and Member States our future status and arrangements with regard to EU agencies. It would not be appropriate to prejudge the outcome of the negotiations.</p>","North East Hertfordshire","Sir Oliver Heald",,"2017-03-06T12:25:44.86Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/705695/answer","Biography information for Sir Oliver Heald","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/705695/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/705695/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2017-02-27","Ministry of Justice: Brexit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what (a) EU agencies and other organisations within her Department's remit the Government plans to withdraw from when the UK leaves the EU, (b) staff time was spent on engagement with those bodies and (c) financial resources were spent on engagement with those bodies in 2015-16.","false","Biography information for Maria Eagle","Garston and Halewood","Maria Eagle","65647"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/705696","Department for Transport","false","2017-03-06","<p>Ministers and officials from the Department for Transport have regular meetings with their counterparts in Transport for London and the Greater London Authority at which a variety of issues are discussed, including the impact of roadworks on London's traffic.</p><p> </p><p>Transport for London, Westminster City Council and the Royal Parks Authority are each responsible for different roads near to Parliament Square, and all roadworks in the Westminster area are planned and managed in such a way as to minimise any disruption to traffic. The London area-wide permitting scheme also allows the relevant highway authority to request that roadworks are carried out at particular times.</p><p> </p><p>TfL and others also regularly discuss the timing of, and potential disruption arising from, works in the vicinity of Parliament Square with the Parliamentary Estate. Where possible, roadworks are scheduled in such a way as to avoid disrupting Parliamentary Business: recent roadworks at Carriage Gates, for example, were scheduled to coincide with the February recess.</p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2017-03-06T15:39:30.3Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/705696/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/705696/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/705696/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-02-27","Parliament Square","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, if he will hold regular discussions with (a) Transport for London and (b) the Mayor of London on ensuring that roadworks, lane closures and maintenance works in Parliament Square and nearby are kept to a minimum at times when Parliament is sitting.","false","Biography information for Sir Greg Knight","East Yorkshire","Sir Greg Knight","65743"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/705697","Northern Ireland Office","false","2017-03-07","<p>The UK unreservedly condemns the use of torture or inhuman treatment. We work hard with our international partners to eradicate this abhorrent practice. We have consistently made clear our absolute opposition to torture and our determination to combat it wherever and whenever it occurs.</p><p> </p><p>Preventing torture and tackling impunity for those who torture are essential components of safeguarding our security and are integral to a fair legal system and the rule of law.</p><p> </p><p>The UK abides by its commitments under international law and expects all countries to comply with their international legal obligations.</p><p> </p><p>The UK Government, including the intelligence and security agencies, never uses torture for any purpose, including to obtain information.</p><p> </p><p>As in any circumstances, if anyone has evidence of any wrongdoing, that should be brought to the attention of the appropriate authorities for investigation.</p><p> </p>","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire",,"2017-03-07T11:23:20.25Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/705697/answer","Biography information for James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/705697/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/705697/answer",,,,,"21","Northern Ireland","Northern Ireland","2017-02-27","Detainees: Northern Ireland","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Northern Ireland, what steps he has taken to investigate allegations on Channel 4's Dispatches programme of 4 February 2017 that members of the armed forces and the RUC were involved in waterboarding detained persons in Northern Ireland in 1972.","false","Biography information for Mr David Anderson","Blaydon","Mr David Anderson","65783"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/705698","Northern Ireland Office","false","2017-03-07","<p>As set out in the recent White Paper (The United Kingdom’s exit from and new partnership with the European Union), the Government will discuss with the EU and Member States our future status and arrangements with regard to EU agencies. It would not be appropriate to prejudge the outcome of the negotiations.</p>","Keighley","Kris Hopkins",,"2017-03-07T11:25:28.167Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/705698/answer","Biography information for Kris Hopkins","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/705698/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/705698/answer",,,,,"21","Northern Ireland","Northern Ireland","2017-02-27","Northern Ireland Office: Brexit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Northern Ireland, what (a) EU agencies and other organisations within his Department's remit the Government plans to withdraw from when the UK leaves the EU, (b) staff time was spent on engagement with those bodies and (c) financial resources were spent on engagement with those bodies in 2015-16.","false","Biography information for Maria Eagle","Garston and Halewood","Maria Eagle","65648"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/705699","Northern Ireland Office","false","2017-03-07","<p>The information is not readily available and could only be obtained at disproportionate cost.</p>","Keighley","Kris Hopkins",,"2017-03-07T11:24:17.873Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/705699/answer","Biography information for Kris Hopkins","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/705699/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/705699/answer",,,,,"21","Northern Ireland","Northern Ireland","2017-02-27","Northern Ireland Office: Procurement","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Northern Ireland, what the procurement spend of his Department was in each year since 2010.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","65692"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/705700","Cabinet Office","false","2017-03-06","<p>The Prime Minister’s Office is an integral part of the Cabinet Office and is included in this reply.</p><p><strong> </strong></p><p>Spend for the department can be found in the Cabinet Office annual report and accounts. The annual report and accounts for financial year 2010-11 to 2015-16 are accessible from the <a href="http://www.gov.uk/" target="_blank">Gov.uk</a> website and the link is below:</p><p> </p><p><a href="http://www.gov.uk/government/publications" target="_blank">www.gov.uk/government/publications</a>.</p>","Ipswich","Ben Gummer","65677","2017-03-06T11:10:35.937Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/705700/answer","Biography information for Ben Gummer","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/705700/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/705700/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2017-02-27","Prime Minister: Procurement","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, what the procurement spend of 10 Downing Street was in each year since 2010.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","65693"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/705701","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-03-02","<p>In the 14 months since the 2 December 2015 vote to support airstrikes against Daesh targets in Syria, the Government has updated the House on four occasions: 16 December 2015, 8 February 2016, 24 May 2016, 3 November 2016. The next update is due soon. It is the intention of this Government to continue to update the House regularly on the progress of the counter Daesh campaign in Iraq and Syria for the foreseeable future.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood",,"2017-03-02T14:50:06.58Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/705701/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/705701/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/705701/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-02-27","Islamic State: Syria","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, with reference to the oral contribution of his predecessor of 2 December 2015, Official Report, column 323, on what occasions the Government has met its commitment to provide quarterly progress reports to the House on military action against ISIL in Syria; and whether the Government plans to continue making such reports to the House on a quarterly basis.","false","Biography information for Patrick Grady","Glasgow North","Patrick Grady","65626"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/705702","Scotland Office","false","2017-03-06","<p>Other than minor or bespoke purchases, the Scotland Office does not normally undertake direct procurement or tendering projects. It uses existing service contracts between suppliers and the Scottish Government or the Ministry of Justice. The Scotland Office do not therefore hold records of procurement spend.</p><p> </p><p><strong> </strong></p><p><strong> </strong></p>","Dumfriesshire, Clydesdale and Tweeddale","David Mundell",,"2017-03-06T12:36:28.143Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/705702/answer","Biography information for David Mundell","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/705702/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/705702/answer",,,,,"2","Scotland","Scotland","2017-02-27","Scotland Office: Procurement","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Scotland, what the procurement spend of his Department was in each year since 2010.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","65694"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/705703","Scotland Office","false","2017-03-06","<p>As set out in the recent White Paper (The United Kingdom’s exit from and new partnership with the European Union), the Government will discuss with the EU and Member States our future status and arrangements with regard to EU agencies. It would not be appropriate to prejudge the outcome of the negotiations.</p>","Dumfriesshire, Clydesdale and Tweeddale","David Mundell",,"2017-03-06T12:41:37.577Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/705703/answer","Biography information for David Mundell","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/705703/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/705703/answer",,,,,"2","Scotland","Scotland","2017-02-27","Scotland Office: Brexit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Scotland, what (a) EU agencies and other organisations within his Department's remit the Government plans to withdraw from when the UK leaves the EU, (b) staff time was spent on engagement with those bodies and (c) financial resources were spent on engagement with those bodies in 2015-16.","false","Biography information for Maria Eagle","Garston and Halewood","Maria Eagle","65649"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/705704","Department for Transport","false","2017-03-07","<p>We estimate that the vast majority of the wrongdoing took place in Germany and so it is appropriate that the German authorities lead the investigation and in pursuing any resolution with Volkswagen. However, I have discussed Volkswagen with my German counterpart and explained that the Government wants Volkswagen’s UK and European customers to receive a warranty when they have the “technical fix” applied to their vehicles. I have not so far discussed this with my American counterparts.</p>","South Holland and The Deepings","Mr John Hayes",,"2017-03-07T14:02:18.357Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/705704/answer","Biography information for Sir John Hayes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/705704/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/705704/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-02-27","Volkswagen","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what recent discussions he has had with his counterparts in Germany and the US on the warranty for the retrofit of Volkswagen cars.","false","Biography information for Stewart Malcolm McDonald","Glasgow South","Stewart Malcolm McDonald","65572"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/705705","Department for Transport","false","2017-03-07","<p>The Government wants Volkswagen to face the appropriate legal consequences for their actions.</p><p> </p><p>On the 22 February I met representatives of legal firms preparing civil action against Volkswagen. They set out how they believe the Government could support their action and I am now considering these requests.</p><p> </p><p>As these matters relate to potential legal action it is not appropriate to comment further.</p>","South Holland and The Deepings","Mr John Hayes",,"2017-03-07T14:06:39.453Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/705705/answer","Biography information for Sir John Hayes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/705705/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/705705/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-02-27","Volkswagen","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what matters were discussed at his meeting with lawyers acting for claimants against Volkswagen on 22 February 2017.","false","Biography information for Stewart Malcolm McDonald","Glasgow South","Stewart Malcolm McDonald","65573"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/705706","Department for Transport","false","2017-03-03","<p>The Driver and Vehicle Standards Agency (DVSA) is taking measures to make the theory and practical driving tests more reflective of a real life driving journey, including a greater emphasis on increasing safety for cyclists.</p><p> </p><p>Theory Test:</p><p> </p><p>The lorry and bus theory tests include questions about dealing with vulnerable road users, including cyclists. Following a review of the Hazard Perception Test (HPT) content, each test now includes at least two clips that involve cyclists. The introduction of computer-generated technology provided the opportunity to include vulnerable road users (VRU) such as cyclists, children and horses. The current focus for future clip development is on driving in bad weather and darkness and these clips will also include vulnerable road users.</p><p> </p><p>Practical Test:</p><p> </p><p>The practical Heavy Goods Vehicle (HGV) driving test involves on road driving for a minimum of 50 minutes and covers a wide variety of roads that allows examiners to assess the driver’s ability to deal safely with vulnerable road users. The practical test is an effective assessment of a driver’s skills, knowledge and competency, including their ability to interact with cyclists. Drivers who show they are not able to interact safely with cyclists will not pass their practical test.</p><p> </p><p>It is compulsory for all professional drivers of HGVs and Passenger Carrying Vehicles (PCV) to complete the Driver Certificate of Professional Competence (Driver CPC) periodic training; this consists of 35 hours training spread over a five year period. Over 100,000 drivers per year complete periodic training focussed on VRUs. The ongoing training includes a wide range of topics including awareness of VRUs in urban areas and city centres.</p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2017-03-03T11:39:04.6Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/705706/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/705706/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/705706/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-02-27","Cycling: Safety","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, pursuant to the Answer of 13 January 2017 to Question 58192, if he will set out recent and planned future changes in the driving test for HGV vehicles to increase safety for cyclists.","false","Biography information for Theresa Villiers","Chipping Barnet","Mrs Theresa Villiers","65630"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/705707","Department for Transport","false","2017-03-07","<p>A total of 234 properties have been acquired under the Exceptional Hardship Scheme (EHS). The Need To Sell (NTS) Scheme replaced the EHS for Phase One in January 2015, 2a in May 2016, and Phase 2b in November 2016; and an additional 56 properties have been acquired under the NTS scheme.</p><p> </p><p>All properties acquired remain in the ownership of the Secretary of State as at 1 March 2017.</p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2017-03-07T13:56:07.693Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/705707/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/705707/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/705707/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-02-27","High Speed 2 Railway Line","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, how many properties purchased under the Exceptional Hardship Scheme in respect of High Speed 2 were still in the ownership of the Government at 1 March 2017.","false","Biography information for Keith Vaz","Leicester East","Keith Vaz","65598"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/705708","Department for Transport","false","2017-03-07","<p><strong> </strong>Southampton City Council was awarded a total of £295,000 in 2016 for the installation of chargepoints for plug-in electric vehicles, as part of Government’s support for efforts to improve air quality in Southampton.</p>","South Holland and The Deepings","Mr John Hayes",,"2017-03-07T15:13:35.337Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/705708/answer","Biography information for Sir John Hayes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/705708/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/705708/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-02-27","Electric Vehicles: Southampton","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what financial support he has allocated to Southampton City Council for charging infrastructure for plug-in electric vehicles.","false","Biography information for Royston Smith","Southampton, Itchen","Royston Smith","65599"
